WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.604
Watch two clear containers.

00:00:01.604 --> 00:00:07.221
In the first, an ice cube sits on a plate and becomes liquid water.

00:00:07.221 --> 00:00:14.843
In the second, a measured spoonful of salt is stirred into room-temperature water until the grains cannot be seen.

00:00:14.843 --> 00:00:18.454
Both solids seem to vanish, but the stories differ.

00:00:18.454 --> 00:00:22.064
The ice changed state: solid water became liquid water.

00:00:22.064 --> 00:00:26.477
The salt spread through another material, water, to make a mixture.

00:00:26.477 --> 00:00:27.681
That is dissolving.

00:00:27.681 --> 00:00:31.291
Looking similar is not enough to name a process.

00:00:31.291 --> 00:00:36.908
We need to track which materials are present, whether a new liquid state formed,

00:00:36.908 --> 00:00:40.920
and what evidence could help us recover the hidden material.

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:48.280
Chemists use three role words.

00:00:48.280 --> 00:00:53.487
The solute is the material that dissolves; in our example, salt is the solute.

00:00:53.487 --> 00:00:57.951
The solvent is the liquid doing the dissolving; water is the solvent.

00:00:57.951 --> 00:01:03.159
The solution is the even-looking mixture produced when the solute spreads through the solvent.

00:01:03.159 --> 00:01:06.879
These are roles in a particular mixture, not permanent surnames.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:13.575
Water is often a solvent, but not every liquid is water, and not every substance dissolves in water.

00:01:13.575 --> 00:01:18.039
The word solution does not mean 'the answer to a question' here.

00:01:18.039 --> 00:01:22.876
It names the whole mixture, including both the dissolved solute and the solvent.

00:01:24.275 --> 00:01:30.350
For a low-risk investigation, use drinking water, table salt, identical clear cups, clean spoons, labels,

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:31.566
and adult supervision.

00:01:31.566 --> 00:01:38.046
Wear eye protection if your class rules require it, wipe spills promptly, and wash hands afterwards.

00:01:38.046 --> 00:01:44.121
The materials are known, but the cups are investigation samples, so do not taste them.

00:01:44.121 --> 00:01:47.361
Never taste an unknown powder to identify it.

00:01:47.361 --> 00:01:51.816
Do not mix household cleaners, medicines, garden chemicals, or mystery substances.

00:01:51.816 --> 00:01:58.701
We can answer strong questions using tiny measured amounts of familiar salt and cool or lukewarm water.

00:01:58.701 --> 00:02:06.396
No flame, kettle, hotplate, or boiling is needed, and the solution should be poured away as an adult directs.

00:02:07.796 --> 00:02:12.729
Let us repair the common claim, 'The salt melted in the water.

00:02:12.729 --> 00:02:18.484
' Melting means a solid becomes its own liquid because of a state change.

00:02:18.484 --> 00:02:23.417
Dissolving means a solute spreads through a solvent to form a solution.

00:02:23.417 --> 00:02:27.939
The salt has not become a little puddle of liquid salt.

00:02:27.939 --> 00:02:32.050
At ordinary classroom temperatures, it remains salt distributed through water.

00:02:32.050 --> 00:02:38.216
Warm water may help salt dissolve faster, but faster dissolving is still dissolving, not melting.

00:02:38.216 --> 00:02:41.094
Temperature alone does not name the process.

00:02:41.094 --> 00:02:46.438
Ask whether one material changed state or whether one material spread through another.

00:02:46.438 --> 00:02:49.316
That question separates the two stories cleanly.

00:02:50.716 --> 00:02:58.966
The cup may look clear after stirring, but clear does not mean pure water and invisible does not mean gone.

00:02:58.966 --> 00:03:02.678
Our particle model shows salt spread among water particles.

00:03:02.678 --> 00:03:06.803
This helps explain why separate grains are no longer visible.

00:03:06.803 --> 00:03:13.403
The dots are symbols, not a photograph, and their size and spacing are not to scale.

00:03:13.403 --> 00:03:16.703
The model gives us an idea to test.

00:03:16.703 --> 00:03:23.716
Evidence from measured mass, saturation, or later recovery supports the claim that salt remains in the solution.

00:03:25.116 --> 00:03:28.006
Now investigate rate: how quickly dissolving happens.

00:03:28.006 --> 00:03:33.787
Put equal amounts of salt into equal volumes of water at the same temperature.

00:03:33.787 --> 00:03:39.156
Stir one cup gently at a steady pace and leave the other still.

00:03:39.156 --> 00:03:46.589
The stirred sample usually loses visible grains sooner because moving water repeatedly brings fresh solvent near the solute.

00:03:46.589 --> 00:03:53.196
Stirring changes the rate, not necessarily the final maximum amount that can dissolve under those conditions.

00:03:53.196 --> 00:03:56.913
To make this a fair comparison, change only stirring.

00:03:56.913 --> 00:03:59.390
Equal salt, equal water, equal cups,

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:05.171
and equal temperature let us connect the different time to the factor we tested.

00:04:10.671 --> 00:04:13.096
Particle size can also affect rate.

00:04:13.096 --> 00:04:19.156
Compare one coarse salt sample with the same mass of fine salt in matching cups.

00:04:19.156 --> 00:04:26.427
Fine grains expose more surface to the water, so they often dissolve faster when all other conditions match.

00:04:26.427 --> 00:04:31.680
Use shop-bought food salt, pour it gently, and keep it away from faces.

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:34.912
Do not grind any material for this activity.

00:04:34.912 --> 00:04:38.144
Again, faster does not mean more can dissolve.

00:04:38.144 --> 00:04:40.568
The fine sample may finish first,

00:04:40.568 --> 00:04:47.031
while both cups end with the same amount dissolved if each began below the saturation limit.

00:04:48.432 --> 00:04:50.647
Temperature can change dissolving rate too.

00:04:50.647 --> 00:04:56.185
An adult prepares equal cups of cool and lukewarm water, never hot enough to burn.

00:04:56.185 --> 00:05:01.354
Add equal amounts of the same salt and stir each in the same way.

00:05:01.354 --> 00:05:05.784
In this salt investigation, the grains may dissolve faster in warmer water.

00:05:05.784 --> 00:05:10.215
Keep rate separate from amount: grains disappearing sooner tell us about time.

00:05:10.215 --> 00:05:15.753
They do not tell us the greatest amount of salt that the water can hold.

00:05:15.753 --> 00:05:20.184
Our result is about this salt and this test, not every solute.

00:05:21.584 --> 00:05:23.677
Amount asks a different question:

00:05:23.677 --> 00:05:29.538
how much solute can dissolve in a fixed volume of solvent under stated conditions?

00:05:29.538 --> 00:05:36.237
Imagine adding salt in small measured portions, stirring for the same generous time after each addition.

00:05:36.237 --> 00:05:38.330
Early portions disappear from sight.

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:43.354
Eventually, extra salt may remain on the bottom even after patient stirring.

00:05:43.354 --> 00:05:48.797
Stirring harder might help grains dissolve sooner, but it cannot guarantee unlimited dissolving.

00:05:48.797 --> 00:05:50.471
A stopwatch answers rate.

00:05:50.471 --> 00:05:54.658
A count or mass of added portions helps answer amount.

00:05:54.658 --> 00:05:57.589
Mixing those questions leads to weak conclusions,

00:05:57.589 --> 00:06:03.031
such as claiming that the fastest cup must always hold the most solute.

00:06:04.432 --> 00:06:07.765
A solution is saturated when, under those conditions,

00:06:07.765 --> 00:06:13.598
it holds as much dissolved solute as it can and added solute remains undissolved.

00:06:13.598 --> 00:06:19.848
We approach this point carefully with small portions rather than dumping in a large pile.

00:06:19.848 --> 00:06:28.181
Salt resting at the bottom after enough stirring is evidence that the current water cannot dissolve all the added salt.

00:06:28.181 --> 00:06:35.681
It is not proof that no salt dissolved; the solution above contains dissolved salt while excess solid remains.

00:06:35.681 --> 00:06:40.264
Saturation depends on the solute, solvent, temperature, and amount of solvent.

00:06:40.264 --> 00:06:44.848
Change those conditions and the maximum dissolved amount may change too.

00:06:50.348 --> 00:06:54.053
Suppose a saturated salt solution has crystals on the bottom.

00:06:54.053 --> 00:06:57.759
Add a measured amount of fresh water and stir again.

00:06:57.759 --> 00:07:02.206
Some remaining crystals may dissolve because there is now more solvent available.

00:07:02.206 --> 00:07:08.506
This is evidence that the earlier limit belonged to that particular amount of water under those conditions;

00:07:08.506 --> 00:07:11.842
the salt had not lost the ability to dissolve.

00:07:11.842 --> 00:07:14.065
Notice what we changed: solvent amount.

00:07:14.065 --> 00:07:19.995
If we also changed temperature, stirring, and salt type, we could not tell which factor mattered.

00:07:19.995 --> 00:07:28.148
Careful investigations isolate one question at a time and record exact amounts instead of relying on cup height or a quick glance.

00:07:29.548 --> 00:07:33.700
How can we show that dissolved salt is still present?

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:34.530
Recover it.

00:07:34.530 --> 00:07:36.191
In an adult-led demonstration,

00:07:36.191 --> 00:07:46.156
place a small amount of salt solution in a wide labelled dish and let water evaporate naturally in a secure place over several days.

00:07:46.156 --> 00:07:47.817
No heating is required.

00:07:47.817 --> 00:07:52.800
As water leaves into the air, salt crystals remain in the dish.

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:59.444
The recovered crystals are strong evidence that the salt was part of the solution, not destroyed.

00:07:59.444 --> 00:08:06.918
Keep the dish away from children, pets, food areas, and open windows, and do not taste the crystals.

00:08:06.918 --> 00:08:12.315
Recovery may be incomplete because some solution can spill or cling to equipment.

00:08:13.716 --> 00:08:16.783
A sensitive balance offers another line of evidence.

00:08:16.783 --> 00:08:21.002
Measure a closed container holding water and a separate salt packet.

00:08:21.002 --> 00:08:25.604
Then combine them without losing material and measure the closed system again.

00:08:25.604 --> 00:08:28.671
The total mass should stay about the same.

00:08:28.671 --> 00:08:32.890
Dissolving changes how salt is spread, not the amount of matter.

00:08:32.890 --> 00:08:40.176
This belongs in an app or adult-led setup because an ordinary kitchen balance may not show small changes clearly.

00:08:40.176 --> 00:08:44.011
A slightly different last digit does not prove matter vanished.

00:08:44.011 --> 00:08:49.379
Good science reports the tool's limit instead of forcing the reading to look perfect.

00:08:50.779 --> 00:08:53.416
Water does not dissolve every material.

00:08:53.416 --> 00:08:57.370
Clean sand settles, cooking oil forms a separate layer,

00:08:57.370 --> 00:09:01.763
and too much salt leaves crystals when saturation is reached.

00:09:01.763 --> 00:09:03.521
These outcomes are different.

00:09:03.521 --> 00:09:07.475
Sand in water is a mixture with undissolved solid.

00:09:07.475 --> 00:09:10.550
Oil and water form separate liquid regions.

00:09:10.550 --> 00:09:17.140
Extra salt can sit beneath a saturated salt solution even though some salt has dissolved.

00:09:17.140 --> 00:09:22.412
Do not call every mixture a solution or decide from colour alone.

00:09:22.412 --> 00:09:29.003
Observe whether the mixture becomes even-looking, whether material settles, and whether it can be recovered.

00:09:29.003 --> 00:09:33.836
These observations tell us what happened, but not every reason why.

00:09:35.235 --> 00:09:37.496
Here is the complete story.

00:09:37.496 --> 00:09:44.728
A solute spreads through a solvent to form a solution; that process is dissolving, not melting.

00:09:44.728 --> 00:09:50.605
Stirring, smaller grains, and temperature can change the rate, which means how fast.

00:09:50.605 --> 00:09:54.221
The maximum amount dissolved is a separate question.

00:09:54.221 --> 00:10:01.002
When added solute remains after thorough stirring, the solution may be saturated under those conditions.

00:10:01.002 --> 00:10:04.166
Adding more solvent can change the limit,

00:10:04.166 --> 00:10:10.042
and natural evaporation can recover the solute as evidence that it never vanished.

00:10:10.042 --> 00:10:15.015
Particle diagrams help us imagine spreading but are simplified, not-to-scale models.

00:10:15.015 --> 00:10:21.796
Use known safe materials, tiny quantities, no tasting, no household chemicals, and no child-led heating.
